From: byron@cc.gatech.edu (Byron A Jeff)
Subject: Re: question about DOS emulator
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1993 01:36:31 GMT

In article <GANDALF.93Aug19202326@damon.ccs.neu.edu>,
Thomas M Farrell <gandalf@ccs.neu.edu> wrote:
>I'm an upcoming consultant that is considering (very strongly) recommending 
>LINUX to my clients as a secondary operating system. 

If your client is not going to run Windows you can make Linux your primary
operating system. With DOS as a spare for anything DOSEMU just won't do.

It's a very good idea. However you do need to stress to clients that it is 
BETA software albeit the best BETA software I've ever seen in my life.
So you'll have the promise and follow through on support. 

I'm doing the same thing. Starting with my department's administrative staff
at Clark Atlanta University.

>
>I've got two questions about the DOS emulator. (For the moment, let's assume
>I can get it compiled correctly and I'm using the newest versions of 
>everything.) The first is, how good is it, really? (in other words, can it

You can get it compiled. Install one of the latest distributions and get the 
current version at tsx-11.mit.edu:/pub/linux/ALPHA/dosemu/current/*.

The current version there if 0.49pl1.

Also it runs on pl10 kernels and better. Of course I recommend pl12.

It's good. It's better that real DOS for the following reasons:

- It doesn't tie up your machine exclusively. You can still do all the
  underlying Unix stuff.
- Since it's a Linux process you can have multiple DOSEMU sessions running
  at once.
- It shares resources now. Your clients will be able to print to a network
  printer for example.
- Due to the most excellent emufs.sys driver DOSEMU sessions have access
  to underlying Linux fs including Network FS. 

In other words it not only gives you DOS but multitasking and the same
level of networking as Novell.

Now it does have a downside. It's not real DOS so it doesn't have immediate
and exclusive access to the physical resources of the machine. So things
like speakers, floppy disks, printer and serial ports will seem sluggish
at times. Think of it as Virtual DOS - It's not the Real Thing (tm).

>really run the majority of DOS stuff, including graphics programs etc?) I am
>aware that some previous versions weren't all that terribly wonderful, but
>I haven't been following it lately.

Text stuff is excellent. I haven't tested it with any graphics programs yet.
Any suggestions?

>
>The second is, can it run under Xwindows?

Yes. But 2 caveats I see so far:

1) The function keys don't work for me.
2) I wouldn't expect any graphics in an Xwindow.

But to be honest it looks best and works best in a Virtual Console. I can't
tell it apart from real DOS.

>
>My apologies for not just shoving it on my own machine and trying it myself to
>see, but I'm presently stuck with very old equipment that can't run Linux. 
><whimper>

Well my advise (which I should start charging for like Ed Carp does ;-)

- You'll need to test extensively each application you want to run on DOSEMU.
  It's still ALPHA software in it's last release. Don't assume because it
  runs some things well that It'll run everything well. For example DOSEMU
  locks up when you select a drop down menu from DOS 5.0 EDIT/QBASIC. Why?
  I don't know.

- Ask you client for a list of applications that they plan to run under DOS.
  It wouldn't be unfair to ask for a test machine also. Then test, test,test
  and test.

- Again be up front with your client.

This is what I've been doing all week . I have 3 converts with one more 
meeting to go.

But when you have DOS, Unix, X windows, and networking all going on at
once, any client will be impressed. And don't forget to put up a cool
GIF in the root Xwindow!

Good Luck,

BAJ
---
