From: byron@cc.gatech.edu (Byron A Jeff)
Subject: Re: A question about the SLS sysinstall script's copyright
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1993 01:58:21 GMT

In article <930819205847.23148@lambada>,
Steve McMahon <steve.mcmahon@lambada.oit.unc.edu> wrote:
>In article <2515es$qp7@sun1.clark.net> stephen@sun1.clark.net (Stephen Balbach) writes:
>>
>>Actually there is a valid point here because Peter has prohibited
>>Slackware from makeing further realeases because they use his sysinstal
>>script, which he is not allowing Slackware to use from what I understand.
>>
>>So a free sysinstall anyone can use would be great!
>>
>
>Peter cannot do that. It's against the GPL.

Yes he can. He wrote the scripts. They are his. 

Now what he cannot do is try to copyright that look and feel thang. If
one of us writes an installation script and looks and acts like the SLS
one then he cannot claim copyright infringement. That's why Slackware
can have series disks and .tgz packages in dos format. It's an idea not
an artifact. sysinstall and doinstall however are software artifacts that
are not based on previous work. Therefore they are Peter's and he can
copyright them. Whether he should or not is up for debate however.

In fact what he's saying is that SLS is the scripts. So if you use the
scripts it must be called SLS. That sounds resonable to me.

Writing an installation script is not rocket scientist material. Someone
should spend an afternoon and just write one. Please don't try to select
me because my wife and kids are coming back from a two week trip tomorrow
and I won't have time for anything in the next few days. All I have time
to do right now is shuffle information and proffer suggestions.

I've noticed that Patrick hasn't had anything to say. He's probably writing
a script even as we speak. What you may want to do instead of whining about
Peter and his copyrights is post what features you'd like to see in an
installation script. I can tell you for a fact that even if he isn't posting
he's out there listening.

Later,

BAJ
